General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3h)(3i) "Full-time employment" means employment which requires the employee to
2 work a regular schedule of hours per day and days per week established as the
3 standard full-time workweek by the employer, but not less than an average of
4 30 hours per week.
5 …."
6 SECTION 1.(c) Article 2 of Chapter 108A of the General Statutes is amended by
7 adding a new Part to read:
8 "Part 4A. Kinship Guardianship Assistance (KinGAP).
9 "§ 108A-50.10. Kinship guardianship assistance.
10 (a) Assistance. – The Division may provide for the financial support of children who
11 have exited foster care into relative guardianship that comply with 42 U.S.C. § 673. A child is
12 eligible for kinship guardianship assistance payments under this Part if the child meets the
13 requirements of subsection (b) of this section.
14 (b) Eligibility. – Until the child is 18 years of age, the child is eligible for kinship
15 guardianship assistance payments if all of the criteria are met:
16 (1) The child was removed from his or her home due to a voluntary placement
17 agreement or as a result of judicial determination to the effect that
18 continuation in the home would be contrary to the welfare of the child.
19 (2) The child was eligible for foster care maintenance payments pursuant to 42
20 U.S.C. § 672 while residing for at least six consecutive months in the home of
21 a licensed prospective relative guardian. "Relative" for the purposes of this
22 Part is a person related to the minor child by blood, marriage, adoption, or an
23 individual that has a substantial relationship with the minor child or the minor
24 child's parent prior to the child being placed in foster care.
25 (3) A determination has been made that reunification or adoption are not
26 appropriate options for the child.
27 (4) The child has attained 10 years of age and demonstrates a strong attachment
28 to the prospective relative guardian and the relative guardian has a strong
29 commitment to caring permanently for the child.
30 (5) At the time of entry into the guardianship agreement, a North Carolina county
31 child welfare agency has placement and care of the child.
32 (6) If a child is 14 years of age, the child has been consulted regarding the kinship
33 guardianship arrangement.
34 (c) Continuation of Assistance. – Individuals or youth who exited foster care under a
35 guardianship assistance agreement may continue to receive kinship guardianship assistance
36 payments after attaining 18 years of age if (i) the individual or child attained 16 years of age
37 before the kinship guardianship assistance agreement became effective, (ii) he or she chooses to
38 continue receiving guardianship services until attaining 21 years of age, and (iii) the Division
39 determines that the individual or child meets any of the following:
40 (1) Is completing secondary education or a program leading to an equivalent
41 credential.
42 (2) Is enrolled in an institution that provides postsecondary or vocational
43 education.
44 (3) Is participating in a program or activity designed to promote or remove
45 barriers to employment.
46 (4) Is employed for at least 80 hours per month.
47 (5) Is incapable of completing the educational or employment requirements of
48 subdivisions (1) through (4) of this subsection due to a medical condition or
49 disability that is supported by regularly updated information in the case plan
50 for the individual.
Page 2 House Bill 795-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (d) Sibling Eligibility. – A child is eligible for kinship guardianship assistance payments
2 if (i) the child has not yet attained 10 years of age, (ii) their sibling meets the requirements of this
3 Part for kinship guardianship assistance payments, and (iii) the county child welfare agency and
4 the prospective relative guardian agree on whether the guardianship arrangement is appropriate
5 for the sibling.
6 (e) In the event of the death or incapacity of the relative guardian, the eligibility of a child
7 to receive kinship guardianship assistance payments under this Part shall not be affected by
8 reason of the replacement of the relative guardian with a successor legal guardian identified in
9 the kinship guardianship assistance agreement entered into under this Part.
10 "§ 108A-50.11. Guardianship assistance.
11 (a) The Division may provide for the financial support of children who exit foster care
12 into legal guardianship with State funds allocated for foster care if the Division determines that
13 all of the following criteria are met:
14 (1) The child has attained 10 years of age and demonstrates a strong attachment
15 to the licensed prospective guardian and the prospective guardian has a strong
16 commitment to caring permanently for the child.
17 (2) The child is in a permanent family placement setting for at least six
18 consecutive months prior to the execution of the guardianship agreement.
19 (3) The prospective guardian is eligible to be appointed as a legal guardian
20 pursuant to G.S. 7B-600(b).
21 (4) The child is unlikely to achieve permanency through reunification or adoption.
22 (5) At the time of entry into the guardianship agreement, a North Carolina county
23 child welfare agency has placement and care of the child.
24 (6) If a child has attained 14 years of age, the child has been consulted regarding
25 the kinship guardianship arrangement.
26 (b) Individuals or youth who exited foster care under a guardianship assistance agreement
27 may continue to receive guardianship assistance payments after attaining 18 years of age if (i)
28 the individual or youth attained 16 years of age before the guardianship assistance agreement
29 became effective, (ii) he or she chooses to continue receiving guardianship services until attaining
30 21 years of age, and (iii) the Division determines that the individual or child meets any of the
31 following:
32 (1) Is completing secondary education or a program leading to an equivalent
33 credential.
34 (2) Is enrolled in an institution that provides postsecondary or vocational
35 education.
36 (3) Is participating in a program or activity designed to promote or remove
37 barriers to employment.
38 (4) Is employed for at least 80 hours per month.
39 (5) Is incapable of completing the educational or employment requirements of
40 subdivisions (1) through (4) of this subsection due to a medical condition or
41 disability that is supported by regularly updated information in the case plan
42 for the individual.
43 "§ 108A-50.12. Guardianship assistance agreement.
44 (a) In order to receive payments under this Part, the county child welfare agency shall (i)
45 negotiate and enter into a written, binding guardianship assistance agreement with the
46 prospective guardian of a child who meets the eligibility requirements of this Part and (ii) provide
47 the prospective guardian with a copy of the agreement.
48 (b) The guardianship agreement shall specify, at a minimum, all of the following:
49 (1) The amount of and manner in which each guardianship assistance payment
50 will be provided under the agreement, and the manner in which the payment
51 may be adjusted.
House Bill 795-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The additional services and assistance that the child and guardian will be
2 eligible for under the agreement.
3 (3) The procedure by which the guardian may apply for additional services as
4 needed.
5 (4) The State will pay the total cost of nonrecurring expenses associated with
6 obtaining legal guardianship of the child to the extent the total cost does not
7 exceed two thousand dollars ($2,000).
8 (c) A guardianship agreement entered into under this section shall provide that the
9 agreement shall remain in effect without regard to the State residency of the guardian.
10 "§ 108A-50.13. Reimbursement for guardians.
11 The guardianship assistance program rates shall reimburse legal and relative guardians for
12 room and board and be set at the same rate as the foster care room and board rates in accordance
13 with rates established under G.S. 108A-49.1."
14 SECTION 2. The Social Services Commission shall adopt temporary rules to
15 implement the provisions of this act. The temporary rules adopted under this act shall remain in
16 effect until permanent rules are adopted that replace those temporary rules.
17 SECTION 3. Section 1 of this act becomes effective July 1, 2025. The remainder of
18 this act is effective when it becomes law.
